---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Types of Whistleblower Cases | whistleblowerawardcalc.com';
const description = 'Types of fraud covered by whistleblower programs: securities, commodities, tax, and government contractor fraud.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Types of Whistleblower Cases</h1>

  <h2>Securities Fraud (SEC)</h2>
  <p>Accounting fraud, insider trading, Ponzi schemes, FCPA (bribery) violations, offering fraud, and investment adviser fraud. The SEC Whistleblower Program has paid over $1.9 billion in awards to more than 400 whistleblowers since 2012.</p>

  <h2>Commodity and Derivatives Fraud (CFTC)</h2>
  <p>Manipulation of commodity prices, fraud in futures and options markets, and spoofing. The CFTC program mirrors the SEC's structure with 10%–30% awards on sanctions over $1 million.</p>

  <h2>Tax Fraud (IRS)</h2>
  <p>Large-scale tax evasion, abusive tax shelters, offshore account concealment, and tax fraud by corporations. The IRS Mandatory Whistleblower Program (§7623(b)) applies when more than $2 million is at issue.</p>

  <h2>Government Contractor Fraud (False Claims Act)</h2>
  <p>Defense contractor overbilling, Medicare/Medicaid fraud, grant fraud, and other schemes to defraud the federal government. The FCA is the largest source of whistleblower recoveries — over $75 billion recovered since 1986.</p>

  <h2>Bank Secrecy Act / Anti-Money Laundering</h2>
  <p>FinCEN's whistleblower program, established by the Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020, covers BSA violations including failure to file SARs and sanctions evasion. Awards: 10%–30% of sanctions over $1 million.</p>

  <h2>State False Claims Acts</h2>
  <p>Over 30 states have their own false claims acts covering state government procurement and Medicaid fraud. Award percentages and procedures vary by state.</p>
</BaseLayout>
